    "komar-natphys-2014",
    "komar-prl-2016",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "malia-nature-2022",
    "nichol-nature-2022",
    "pirandola-natphoton-2018",
    "proctor-prl-2018",
    "wehner-science-2018",
    "xia-prl-2020",
    "zhang-zhuang-qst-2021",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="sensing" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Networked &amp; distributed quantum sensing</h1>
        <p>
          A single quantum sensor that uses an entangled probe can push its
          precision from the standard quantum limit (uncertainty falling as
          1/√N in the number of probes) toward the Heisenberg limit
          (1/N) <SourceNote id="giovannetti-natphoton-2011" />. The networked
          version distributes that entanglement <em>across separated nodes</em>:
          a shared multipartite state lets the network estimate a
          <em>global</em> parameter — a weighted combination of quantities each
          sensed locally — better than any set of independent sensors
          could <SourceNote id="zhang-zhuang-qst-2021" />. That is the sensing
          regime where the quantum network is the enabling resource, not an
          implementation detail.
        </p>
        <p>
          The single-sensor foundations are covered by the standard quantum-sensing
          review <SourceNote id="degen-rmp-2017" />; what follows is the line that
          needs a network. Wehner et al. 2018 list both clock synchronisation and
          telescope-baseline extension as quantum-internet applications, sitting
          above the entanglement-distribution stage of the
          roadmap <SourceNote id="wehner-science-2018" />. Sensing consumes
          entanglement differently from QKD or distributed computing — some
          protocols tolerate lower fidelity, but timing precision and the
          source-of-randomness constraints are tighter <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <Callout label="The precision limits — shot-noise, Heisenberg, entanglement">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Standard quantum limit (shot-noise limit).</strong> The best
              precision from N independent probes (atoms or photons) measured and
              averaged: the uncertainty shrinks only as 1/√N — the same statistical
              scaling as averaging more coin flips. It is the baseline a quantum sensor
              tries to beat.</li>
            <li><strong>Heisenberg limit.</strong> The ultimate precision quantum
              mechanics allows when the N probes are entangled and act together — the
              uncertainty shrinks as 1/N, a quadratic improvement over the standard
              quantum limit. Reaching it requires entanglement.</li>
            <li><strong>Multipartite entanglement.</strong> Entanglement shared among
              three or more parties at once, not just a pair, so a measurement at one
              node is correlated with all the others. It is what lets separated sensors
              behave as one instrument.</li>
            <li><strong>Global parameter.</strong> A single quantity built from values
              in several places at once — say a weighted average of the field at each
              node — rather than one local reading.</li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </header>

      <section id="clocks" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Networked atomic clocks</h2>
        <p>
          Distributing an entangled (GHZ-type) state between the qubits of
          geographically separated optical atomic clocks lets the network's joint
          frequency measurement scale at the Heisenberg limit rather than the
          shot-noise limit, while the protocol's internal structure provides
          security against both external and internal
          attackers <SourceNote id="komar-natphys-2014" />. A concrete neutral-atom
          implementation builds the GHZ state through Rydberg-mediated local gates
          and single-photon links between
          ensembles <SourceNote id="komar-prl-2016" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The first experimental realisation entangled two <sup>88</sup>Sr<sup>+</sup> ions about two
          metres apart over a photonic link and showed the frequency-comparison
          uncertainty drop by ≈√2 — the Heisenberg-limited value for two nodes —
          demonstrating the clock-network advantage between separately-housed,
          remotely-entangled systems <SourceNote id="nichol-nature-2022" />.
        </p>
        <Callout label="Optical clocks, GHZ states, and Rydberg gates">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Optical atomic clock.</strong> A clock that counts the ticks of
              an atom's optical-frequency transition (hundreds of THz) rather than a
              microwave one (as in caesium clocks), giving far higher precision.</li>
            <li><strong>GHZ state.</strong> A maximally-entangled state of many qubits
              (after Greenberger–Horne–Zeilinger) in which every party is correlated
              together — the workhorse entangled state for clock networks.</li>
            <li><strong>Rydberg-mediated.</strong> Built using atoms briefly excited to
              high-energy "Rydberg" states, which interact strongly across micron
              distances; that strong interaction drives the fast entangling gates
              between atoms in an ensemble.</li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="telescopy" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Quantum-enhanced telescopy</h2>
        <p>
          Very-long-baseline interferometry resolves fine detail by combining
          light collected at widely separated telescopes; the limit is the loss in
          physically carrying one telescope's photons to the other. Gottesman,
          Jennewein and Croke showed the physical link can be replaced with
          pre-shared entanglement, so the effective baseline — and the angular
          resolution — extends far beyond what a direct optical connection
          allows <SourceNote id="gottesman-prl-2012" />. The scheme turns
          astronomical interferometry into a consumer of distributed Bell pairs.
        </p>
        <p>
          Khabiboulline et al. recast this using quantum memories and
          quantum-network primitives, cutting the entanglement-distribution cost
          so the approach reads as a service on a quantum-internet stack rather
          than a one-off link <SourceNote id="khabiboulline-prl-2019" />.
        </p>
        <Callout label="Interferometry and baseline">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Interferometry.</strong> Combining the light waves collected at
              two telescopes and reading their interference pattern; the finer the
              interference can be measured, the finer the detail that can be resolved.</li>
            <li><strong>Baseline.</strong> The distance between the two telescopes.
              Angular resolution improves as the baseline grows — which is why
              extending it (here, with shared entanglement) is the whole point.</li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="distributed" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Distributed multiparameter estimation</h2>
        <p>
          Beyond clocks and telescopes, the general problem is estimating a global
          function of parameters sensed locally at different nodes. Proctor, Knott
          and Dunningham set up the framework and identify when entanglement
          between nodes beats purely local
          strategies <SourceNote id="proctor-prl-2018" />; Eldredge et al. give
          optimal protocols for measuring a linear combination of fields across the
          network, together with a guarantee that only the intended recipient
          learns the result — the same trust model as the rest of the quantum
          internet <SourceNote id="eldredge-pra-2018" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The advantage has been shown on hardware across platforms: a
          continuous-variable three-node photonic
          network <SourceNote id="guo-natphys-2020" />, a reconfigurable
          radio-frequency photonic sensor network <SourceNote id="xia-prl-2020" />,
          and mode-entangled spin-squeezed atomic
          ensembles <SourceNote id="malia-nature-2022" />. For the photonic-probe
          background these build on, see the photonic-sensing
          review <SourceNote id="pirandola-natphoton-2018" />.
        </p>
        <Callout label="Continuous- vs discrete-variable, and spin squeezing">
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Continuous-variable (CV) vs discrete-variable (DV).</strong> Two
              ways to carry quantum information: DV in countable states (a single
              photon's polarisation, a qubit), CV in continuous quantities (the
              amplitude and phase of a light field). CV sensing uses squeezed light; DV
              uses single photons or qubits.</li>
            <li><strong>Spin-squeezed state.</strong> An entangled state of many atoms
              in which the quantum noise of the measured quantity is squeezed below the
              standard-quantum-limit level — improving precision, at the cost of extra
              noise in a quantity you do not care about.</li>
          </ul>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="demonstrations" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Demonstrations to date</h2>
        <p>
          The hardware realisations across the clock-network and distributed-sensing
          lines. Early and small-scale, but each shows an entanglement advantage on
          real apparatus rather than in simulation.
        </p>
        <div class="demo-table-wrap">
          <table class="demo-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">Platform</th>
                <th scope="col">Scale</th>
                <th scope="col">Demonstrated result</th>
                <th scope="col">Source</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Trapped ions (<sup>88</sup>Sr<sup>+</sup>)</th>
                <td>2 nodes, ~2 m, photonic link</td>
                <td>Entangled optical-clock comparison; frequency-comparison uncertainty
                  reduced by ≈√2 — the Heisenberg-limited value for two nodes</td>
                <td><SourceNote id="nichol-nature-2022" /></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Spin-squeezed atomic ensembles</th>
                <td>Mode-entangled, multi-mode (lab)</td>
                <td>Distributed sensing with mode-entangled spin-squeezed states, below
                  the standard quantum limit</td>
                <td><SourceNote id="malia-nature-2022" /></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">RF-photonic sensor network</th>
                <td>Reconfigurable multi-node (lab)</td>
                <td>Entanglement-enhanced estimation of a weighted radio-frequency
                  signal, with reconfigurable node weighting</td>
                <td><SourceNote id="xia-prl-2020" /></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">Continuous-variable photonic</th>
                <td>3 nodes (lab)</td>
                <td>Distributed phase estimation below the standard quantum limit via
                  multipartite CV entanglement</td>
                <td><SourceNote id="guo-natphys-2020" /></td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="papers" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Key papers</h2>
        <p>
          The network-required sensing line, grouped from the metrology foundations
          through the two flagship use cases to distributed estimation and its
          experimental demonstrations.
        </p>

        {paperGroups.map((group) => (
          <div class="paper-group">
            <h3>{group.heading}</h3>
            <ul class="paper-list">
              {group.papers.map((p) => (
                <li class="paper">
                  <a class="paper__title" href={p.href} rel="noopener" target="_blank">
                    {p.title}
                  </a>
                  <span class="paper__cite">{p.cite}</span>
                  <p class="paper__review">{p.review}</p>
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        ))}
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

